Using De-Moivre's Theorem, we have $(\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)^3 = \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta.$<end think>

Computing using De-Moivre's Theorem:
\begin{align*}
(\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)^3 &= \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta \\
\cos^3 \theta - 3 \cos \theta \sin^2 \theta + 3 i  \cos^2 \theta \sin \theta + i^3 \sin^3 \theta &= \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta \\
\cos^3 \theta - 3 \cos \theta \sin^2 \theta  + i 3 \cos \theta \sin \theta - i \sin^3 \theta &= \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta \\
\cos^3 \theta - \sin^2 \theta \cdot 3 \cos \theta  + i 3 \cos \theta \sin \theta - i \sin^3 \theta &= \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta \\
\cos^3 \theta - 3 \cos \theta(1 - \cos^2 \theta)  + i 3 \cos \theta \sin \theta - i \sin^3 \theta &= \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta \\
\cos^3 \theta - 3 \cos \theta + 3 \cos^3 \theta  + 3 i  \cos \theta \sin \theta - i \sin^3 \theta &= \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta \\
4 \cos^3 \theta - 3 \cos \theta + 3 i  \cos \theta \sin \theta - i \sin^3 \theta &= \cos 3 \theta + i \sin 3 \theta \\
\cos 3 \theta &= 4 \cos^3 \theta - 3 \cos \theta \\
\sin 3 \theta &= 3 \sin \theta - 4 \sin^3 \theta
\end{align*}
<end think>

